It’s so easy to just expect that food will be there for us when we need it. I learned that the ag industry is quite fragile, and personally, I’ve grown even deeper respect for the myriad of people who ensure that the rest of us get the food we need—even during a crisis.

Some of the more libertarian ideals in rural parts of WA state had those communities wondering if the choices made in Olympia were the right ones for them and whether they should be able to decide for themselves, county by county,  how they address the pandemic.

They are nervous about the virus—just like others in metro areas. But their rural way of life is different, it’s built for isolation. Their kids were out of school and they were navigating parenting and working just like many of us.

There was a bottleneck for the cattle industry at the packing plants that were causing some scarcity for consumers and forcing ranchers to ponder some tough decisions about the immediate future of their ranches and the possible effects for years down the road.
So I spent some time learning how one of the longest-running family-operations in the state were navigating this slowly unfolding—and ongoing—disaster that America continued to navigate this year.

Visiting my local grocery store as the pandemic began, I noticed empty shelves that once were filled with beef products for consumers. The prices of carne asada tacos at my local food truck were a dollar more than usual, my restaurant owner friend was raising his prices.

WATCH: I spent time this year learning about the fragility of eastern WA’s cattle industry amid the #pandemic  w/ a fifth-generation family-owned operation in Adams County for this week’s episode of The New Normal on @crosscut @kcts9 - https://t.co/KWWdzAeuoM https://t.co/RO0lEnCdOL

This was just a short experience of my own while covering far right culture during the Obama era, @josh_levin current reporting on the podcast is second to none. Give it a listen.
Fast forward a decade to today, a quick phone call indicates the church is still around when they answered the phone and confirmed the number I was calling is correct.

The exchange didn’t last much longer than 5 minutes. He turned and entered the church and the owners of it wouldn’t let me inside for his speech. I tried visiting on other occasions too, but never got past the lobby.

I’m not; am actually a white presenting person with LatinX roots, but my hair and facial features made him think otherwise. He started into a diatribe about how Jews control the media and are everything that is wrong with America.

I heard he was coming to the small town on I was living in on a book tour, so I placed myself outside the white nationalist church and waited for him to arrive. When he did, he agreed to some portraits but then immediately stereotyped me as being Jewish.
